"id\": \"c3d0fbc1-2b16-4c23-8201-7e24eee136bf\", \"tool_call_id\": \"call_mReQj260CWQUAA1Rp6cqmkUt\", \"status\": \"success\"}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 61, \"prompt_tokens\": 2212, \"total_tokens\": 2273, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 0, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 2048}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-4o-mini-2024-07-18\", \"system_fingerprint\": \"fp_373a14eb6f\", \"id\": \"chatcmpl-DCp5sLiTCDbLN18f4qDB3bmtNOQV3\", \"service_tier\": \"default\", \"finish_reason\": \"tool_calls\", \"logprobs\": null}, \"type\": \"ai\", \"id\": \"lc_run--019c905f-9dc8-72b1-96c4-d1ab6dcd5856-0\", \"tool_calls\": [{\"name\": \"document_retriever\", \"args\": {\"s3_uri\": \"s3://agentic-wf/mcp/arxiv_consolidated/download_article-3f4b474fcb286355fc6637db9295740bb01ce3fc.txt\", \"query\": \"introduction\"}, \"id\": \"call_k2VdJab1HxhQfRUp5bbtIS6B\", \"type\": \"tool_call\"}], \"usage_metadata\": {\"input_tokens\": 2212, \"output_tokens\": 61, \"total_tokens\": 2273, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 2048}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 0}}, \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"ToolMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"tected by non-local topology, MZMs make themselves a\\npromising candidate for fault-tolerant topological quan-\\ntum computation[3\\u20135]. From experimental perspective,\\nMajorana signatures have been reported in 1d Rashba\\nnaowires approximated to conventional superconduc-\\ntors [6\\u201312], 2d topological insulator-superconductor het-\\nerostructures [13\\u201317], and Fe-based superconductor with\\ntopological protected surfase state.[18\\u201323].\\nWhen di-\\nrectly contact with a normal lead (NL) in transport mea-\\nsurements, the fraction signature of the MZM is fragile\\nand depends on meticulous adjustment of parameters. In\\norder to detect the fractionally quantized signal such as\\nconductance, quantum dot (QD) assistant systems have\\nbeen proposed [24\\u201326]. In those systems, the Kondo reso-\\nnance peak [27\\u201329] is dramatically modified by the MZM\\nthrough an anti-Fano resonance in a wide parameter re-\\ngion. This makes the MZM-QD-NL system a promising\\nsetup to unambiguously detect MZMs..\\n\\na proper observable that unambiguously captures the properties of the screening process across\\ntemperatures. A clear crossover from conventional Kondo spin screening to spin-charge-entangled\\nscreening is observed. Taking into account the overlap between Majorana zero modes, the A \\u2297N\\nboundary condition reduces to a normal one, yet the spin-charge-entangled screening is protected\\nby the SUL(2) symmetry. On the other hand, perturbation that breaks the SUL(2) symmetry can\\ndestroy the screening singlet, while leaving the low-temperature A \\u2297N boundary condition intact.\\nI.\\nINTRODUCTION\\nMajorana zero modes (MZMs)[1, 2], characterized\\nby the self-conjugation property and exact zero-energy\\nexcitation, represents a frontier in condesed matters.\\nCrucially, obeying the non-Abelian statistics and pro-\\ntected by non-local topology, MZMs make themselves a\\npromising candidate for fault-tolerant topological quan-\\ntum computation[3\\u20135]. From experimental perspective,.\\n\\nnance peak [27\\u201329] is dramatically modified by the MZM\\nthrough an anti-Fano resonance in a wide parameter re-\\ngion. This makes the MZM-QD-NL system a promising\\nsetup to unambiguously detect MZMs.\\nThough characteristic spectrum signatures has been\\nobtained using unbiased many-body methods like nu-\\nmerical renormalization group (NRG) [30], the underly-\\n\\u2217Y. Chen and H. Shen contributed equally to this work.\\n\\u2020 suwei@sicnu.edu.cn\\n\\u2021 rwang89@nju.edu.cn\\ning physics that drive the interplay between the Kondo\\nscreening and the QD-MZM coupling have been de-\\nbated for a long time [31\\u201335].\\nOn one hand, it has\\nbeen shown that at very low temperature, the system\\nis subjected to the A \\u2297N boundary condition (BC)\\ndue to the QD-MZM coupling [32]. Here A \\u2297N repre-\\nsents the Andreev-normal boundary conditions for spin-\\n\\u2191/\\u2193electrons, respectively.\\nOn the other hand, the\\ntemperature-dependent entropy of the MZM-QD subsys-\\ntem (Simp) suggests that the Kondo-like screening pro-.\\n\\nbroken down but the SCE screening preserves. The Lz\\nterm which breaks the SUL(2) symmtry, however, de-\\nstroys the SCE singlet but leaving the A \\u2297N BC un-\\ntouched. Our results are enlightened to both the Kondo\\nand TSC community to dispel the obstacle in theoretical\\npredictions and experimental measurements.\\nII.\\nMODEL AND METHOD\\nThe system we consider is composed of an open topo-\\nlogical superconducting (TSC) wire, a quantum dot, and\\na normal lead as shown in Fig. 1(a). The TSC hosts a\\nlocalized MZM at each boundary, with one side couples\\nto the QD. The Halmitonian is given by H = H0 + H\\u2032.\\nHere H0 is the SUL(2) symmetric Kondo-like impurity\\nmodel of the following form\\nH0 = iJM\\u03b3\\u22121LQD \\u00b7 \\u03be0 + JKLQD \\u00b7 S0 +\\nX\\nk\\n\\u03f5kc\\u2020\\nk\\u03c3ck\\u03c3, (1)\\nwith \\u03b3\\u22121 \\u2261(f + f \\u2020) the MZM operator at the boundary\\nof the TSC, and\\n[\\u03bex\\n0 , \\u03bey\\n0, \\u03bez\\n0] \\u2261\\nh\\ni(c\\u2020\\n0\\u2193\\u2212c0\\u2193), \\u2212(c\\u2020\\n0\\u2193+ c0\\u2193), i(c\\u2020\\n0\\u2191\\u2212c0\\u2191)\\ni\\nform irreducible tensor operators of the SUL(2) group,\\nwhere c0\\u03c3 = P ck\\u03c3 is the local electron annihilation\\noperator.\", \"type\": \"tool\", \"name\": \"document_retriever\", \"id\": \"aa46a213-251f-4e92-bbaa-a4fac1b9947e\", \"tool_call_id\": \"call_k2VdJab1HxhQfRUp5bbtIS6B\", \"status\": \"success\"}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 61, \"prompt_tokens\": 3338, \"total_tokens\": 3399, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 0, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 2176}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-4o-mini-2024-07-18\", \"system_fingerprint\": \"fp_373a14eb6f\", \"id\": \"chatcmpl-DCp633Mp1rkBzJNFPU8VZSS4qkSj8\", \"service_tier\": \"default\", \"finish_reason\": \"tool_calls\", \"logprobs\": null}, \"type\": \"ai\", \"id\": \"lc_run--019c905f-c6f5-7f13-bb5e-7369f0be5ebc-0\", \"tool_calls\": [{\"name\": \"document_retriever\", \"args\": {\"s3_uri\": \"s3://agentic-wf/mcp/arxiv_consolidated/download_article-3f4b474fcb286355fc6637db9295740bb01ce3fc.txt\", \"query\": \"core contributions\"}, \"id\": \"call_laFsjXwMt1TsXYbbUQ9UmsNd\", \"type\": \"tool_call\"}], \"usage_metadata\": {\"input_tokens\": 3338, \"output_tokens\": 61, \"total_tokens\": 3399, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 2176}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 0}}, \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}]}, \"tags\": [\"graph:step:7\"], \"metadata\": {\"langgraph_step\": 7, \"langgraph_node\": \"tools\", \"langgraph_triggers\": [\"branch:to:tools\"], \"langgraph_path\": [\"__pregel_pull\", \"tools\"], \"langgraph_checkpoint_ns\": \"tools:e3d7b828-2ca8-87ca-af39-a7d0baa28050\"}, \"kwargs\": {\"name\": \"tools\"}}",
