: 2212, \"output_tokens\": 61, \"total_tokens\": 2273, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 2048}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 0}}, \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"ToolMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"tected by non-local topology, MZMs make themselves a\\npromising candidate for fault-tolerant topological quan-\\ntum computation[3\\u20135]. From experimental perspective,\\nMajorana signatures have been reported in 1d Rashba\\nnaowires approximated to conventional superconduc-\\ntors [6\\u201312], 2d topological insulator-superconductor het-\\nerostructures [13\\u201317], and Fe-based superconductor with\\ntopological protected surfase state.[18\\u201323].\\nWhen di-\\nrectly contact with a normal lead (NL) in transport mea-\\nsurements, the fraction signature of the MZM is fragile\\nand depends on meticulous adjustment of parameters. In\\norder to detect the fractionally quantized signal such as\\nconductance, quantum dot (QD) assistant systems have\\nbeen proposed [24\\u201326]. In those systems, the Kondo reso-\\nnance peak [27\\u201329] is dramatically modified by the MZM\\nthrough an anti-Fano resonance in a wide parameter re-\\ngion. This makes the MZM-QD-NL system a promising\\nsetup to unambiguously detect MZMs..\\n\\na proper observable that unambiguously captures the properties of the screening process across\\ntemperatures. A clear crossover from conventional Kondo spin screening to spin-charge-entangled\\nscreening is observed. Taking into account the overlap between Majorana zero modes, the A \\u2297N\\nboundary condition reduces to a normal one, yet the spin-charge-entangled screening is protected\\nby the SUL(2) symmetry. On the other hand, perturbation that breaks the SUL(2) symmetry can\\ndestroy the screening singlet, while leaving the low-temperature A \\u2297N boundary condition intact.\\nI.\\nINTRODUCTION\\nMajorana zero modes (MZMs)[1, 2], characterized\\nby the self-conjugation property and exact zero-energy\\nexcitation, represents a frontier in condesed matters.\\nCrucially, obeying the non-Abelian statistics and pro-\\ntected by non-local topology, MZMs make themselves a\\npromising candidate for fault-tolerant topological quan-\\ntum computation[3\\u20135]. From experimental perspective,.\\n\\nnance peak [27\\u201329] is dramatically modified by the MZM\\nthrough an anti-Fano resonance in a wide parameter re-\\ngion. This makes the MZM-QD-NL system a promising\\nsetup to unambiguously detect MZMs.\\nThough characteristic spectrum signatures has been\\nobtained using unbiased many-body methods like nu-\\nmerical renormalization group (NRG) [30], the underly-\\n\\u2217Y. Chen and H. Shen contributed equally to this work.\\n\\u2020 suwei@sicnu.edu.cn\\n\\u2021 rwang89@nju.edu.cn\\ning physics that drive the interplay between the Kondo\\nscreening and the QD-MZM coupling have been de-\\nbated for a long time [31\\u201335].\\nOn one hand, it has\\nbeen shown that at very low temperature, the system\\nis subjected to the A \\u2297N boundary condition (BC)\\ndue to the QD-MZM coupling [32]. Here A \\u2297N repre-\\nsents the Andreev-normal boundary conditions for spin-\\n\\u2191/\\u2193electrons, respectively.\\nOn the other hand, the\\ntemperature-dependent entropy of the MZM-QD subsys-\\ntem (Simp) suggests that the Kondo-like screening pro-.\\n\\nbroken down but the SCE screening preserves. The Lz\\nterm which breaks the SUL(2) symmtry, however, de-\\nstroys the SCE singlet but leaving the A \\u2297N BC un-\\ntouched. Our results are enlightened to both the Kondo\\nand TSC community to dispel the obstacle in theoretical\\npredictions and experimental measurements.\\nII.\\nMODEL AND METHOD\\nThe system we consider is composed of an open topo-\\nlogical superconducting (TSC) wire, a quantum dot, and\\na normal lead as shown in Fig. 1(a). The TSC hosts a\\nlocalized MZM at each boundary, with one side couples\\nto the QD. The Halmitonian is given by H = H0 + H\\u2032.\\nHere H0 is the SUL(2) symmetric Kondo-like impurity\\nmodel of the following form\\nH0 = iJM\\u03b3\\u22121LQD \\u00b7 \\u03be0 + JKLQD \\u00b7 S0 +\\nX\\nk\\n\\u03f5kc\\u2020\\nk\\u03c3ck\\u03c3, (1)\\nwith \\u03b3\\u22121 \\u2261(f + f \\u2020) the MZM operator at the boundary\\nof the TSC, and\\n[\\u03bex\\n0 , \\u03bey\\n0, \\u03bez\\n0] \\u2261\\nh\\ni(c\\u2020\\n0\\u2193\\u2212c0\\u2193), \\u2212(c\\u2020\\n0\\u2193+ c0\\u2193), i(c\\u2020\\n0\\u2191\\u2212c0\\u2191)\\ni\\nform irreducible tensor operators of the SUL(2) group,\\nwhere c0\\u03c3 = P ck\\u03c3 is the local electron annihilation\\noperator.\", \"type\": \"tool\", \"name\": \"document_retriever\", \"id\": \"aa46a213-251f-4e92-bbaa-a4fac1b9947e\", \"tool_call_id\": \"call_k2VdJab1HxhQfRUp5bbtIS6B\", \"status\": \"success\"}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 61, \"prompt_tokens\": 3338, \"total_tokens\": 3399, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 0, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 2176}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-4o-mini-2024-07-18\", \"system_fingerprint\": \"fp_373a14eb6f\", \"id\": \"chatcmpl-DCp633Mp1rkBzJNFPU8VZSS4qkSj8\", \"service_tier\": \"default\", \"finish_reason\": \"tool_calls\", \"logprobs\": null}, \"type\": \"ai\", \"id\": \"lc_run--019c905f-c6f5-7f13-bb5e-7369f0be5ebc-0\", \"tool_calls\": [{\"name\": \"document_retriever\", \"args\": {\"s3_uri\": \"s3://agentic-wf/mcp/arxiv_consolidated/download_article-3f4b474fcb286355fc6637db9295740bb01ce3fc.txt\", \"query\": \"core contributions\"}, \"id\": \"call_laFsjXwMt1TsXYbbUQ9UmsNd\", \"type\": \"tool_call\"}], \"usage_metadata\": {\"input_tokens\": 3338, \"output_tokens\": 61, \"total_tokens\": 3399, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 2176}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 0}}, \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"ToolMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"the MZMs are decoupled from the QD-NL subsystem, and\\n(a2) the SCE screening cloud with an A \\u2297B BC. (b-d) Nu-\\nmerical results for different JM. JK is chosen as 0.2 to display\\nthe local moment fixed point at Simp = 2ln2. (b) The impu-\\nrity entropy Simp.\\n(c) The spin and charge components of\\nthe correlation function. Both of them are normalized to the\\nzero-temperature result \\u02dcIi = Ii/Ii(T = 0).\\ntemperatures.\\nIn practical calculations, the integral is\\nrepalced by a summation over the bath sites of the Wil-\\nson chain, which is obtained by a tranformation from\\nthe original Hamiltonian. Within the framework of full\\ndensity matrix (FDM), the correlation functions can be\\ncalculated with a single \\u201cforward\\u201d NRG sweep after ob-\\ntaining the reduced density matrix for each site (See\\nappendices for details).\\nWe point out that our finite-\\ntemperature correlator method can be applied to a broad\\nclass of composite or artificial impurity systems, provid-.\\n\\nMZM that couples the rest electrons in the NL. As a re-\\nsult, the Kondo fixed point becomes unstable, and a new\\nenergy scale denoted TSCE emerges as the signature of\\nthe IR fixed point. An A \\u2297N boundary condition is met\\nas temperature is lowered below TSCE (about 10\\u221213 for\\nJM = 1e \\u22127). The Simp = 1\\n2ln2 plateau indicates an in-\\nfrared (IR) strong coupling fixed point (SCFP) induced\\nby the decoupled MZM \\u03b3\\u22122, and the schematic is in Fig.\\n2(a2). The physics of the IR SCFP is proved to be same\\nas the two-channel Kondo model in the sense of the low-\\nenergy-effective Hamiltonian and non-Fermi liquid exci-\\ntations. The effect of the A \\u2297N BC is also revealed by\\nthe LDoS where the pseudospin-up part divide into two\\ncomponents \\u03c1\\u2191and A\\u2191. Each of them contributes half to\\nthe resonance peak [31, 36].\\nResults for the integrated correlation functions are\\nshown in Fig. 2(c). For TSCE \\u226aTK, the contribution of\\nIC in the screening cloud IL \\u2261IS + IC is neglectable..\\n\\nthe resonance peak [31, 36].\\nResults for the integrated correlation functions are\\nshown in Fig. 2(c). For TSCE \\u226aTK, the contribution of\\nIC in the screening cloud IL \\u2261IS + IC is neglectable.\\nHowever, one can see that at the Kondo fixed point\\n(Simp = ln2 of the dark solid line in Fig. 2(b)), the spin\\nscreening cloud (the blue curves in Fig. 2(c)) has com-\\npletely established, while the charge cloud only start to\\nestablish after T \\u2272TK. For a medium JK = 1e \\u22124, the\\nSimp = ln2 plateau just disappears, as shown by the dark\\ndashed line in Fig. 2(b). For a lager JK \\u22731e \\u22124, the\\nlocal moment fixed point flows directly to the SCE fixed\\npoint skipping the spin Kondo SCFP, and the screen-\\ning process of spin and charge DoF can happens almost\\nmeanwhile, as illustrated by the dotted lines in Fig. 2(c).\\nThe physical meaning of the character temperatures be-\\ncomes explicit now. The definition of TK is analogous to\\nthe conventional Kondo temperature when a spin screen-.\\n\\nior with three characteristic energy scales TK, TSCE, TM\\nin order. The SCE screening process, however, preserves\\nto low temperatures under TK instead of disappearing\\nwith the vanishment of the Simp = ln2 plateau (together\\nwith the topological degeneracy), as shown by the charge\\ncomponent of the correlation functions IC in Fig. 3(c)\\n(red solid line).\\nThe local spectrum of the MZM-QD\\nsubsystem is plotted in Fig. 1(c).\\nIf we turn up the value of \\u03f5m until the Simp = 1\\n2ln2\\nplateau disappears, the two energy scales TM and TSCE\\nbecomes the same.\\nThis can be seen clearly from the\\nevolution of IC.\\nThe evolution also implies that the\\nSCE screening is even enhanced by the MZM-MZM cou-\\npling. Independently, the fading of the 1\\n2 plateau of the\\nanomolous LDoS A\\u2191in Fig. 3(d) indicates the violation\\nof the A\\u2297N boundary condition. Thus it should be clar-\\nified that, the establishment of the SCE screening cloud\\ndoes not dependent on the existence of the A \\u2297N BC.\", \"type\": \"tool\", \"name\": \"document_retriever\", \"id\": \"0b90252c-3cd8-467b-a201-690b256bb35c\", \"tool_call_id\": \"call_laFsjXwMt1TsXYbbUQ9UmsNd\", \"status\": \"success\"}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"### Summary of the Paper: \\\"Multi-scale competition in the Majorana-Kondo system\\\"\\n\\n#### Introduction:\\nThe paper discusses Majorana zero modes (MZMs), which are characterized by their self-conjugation property and exact zero-energy excitation. MZMs are deemed a breakthrough in condensed matter physics due to their non-Abelian statistics and their potential for fault-tolerant topological quantum computation. The authors highlight the significant experimental evidence for MZMs in one-dimensional (1D) and two-dimensional (2D) systems, emphasizing the delicate nature of the MZM signature when interacting with normal leads in transport measurements. The research focuses on systems assisted by quantum dots (QDs) where MZMs can modify the Kondo resonance, leading to observable signals critical for detection.\\n\\n#### Core Contributions:\\n1. **Theoretical Framework**: The paper presents a theoretical model that combines a topological superconducting (TSC) wire with a quantum dot and normal lead. It describes how the system transitions from conventional Kondo screening to spin-charge-entangled (SCE) screening via interactions with MZMs.\\n\\n2. **Boundary Conditions**: An essential result is the identification of boundary conditions (A \\u2297 N) that emerge due to the QD-MZM coupling. The authors explore how variations in temperature affect these boundary conditions and their implications for the Kondo-like screening process.\\n\\n3. **Numerical Calculations**: Through numerical methods, the research details the temperature-dependent entropy of the MZM-QD subsystem, revealing three characteristic energy scales that dictate system behavior: Kondo temperature (TK), a signature energy scale for SCE (TSCE), and another energy scale associated with MZMs (TM). \\n\\n4. **Effective Hamiltonian**: The findings indicate that the low-energy-effective Hamiltonian behaves similarly to the two-channel Kondo model, leading to non-Fermi liquid excitations. The paper shows how perturbations that break symmetry can influence screening, yet certain protections remain intact at low temperatures.\\n\\n5. **Implications for Experimentation**: The results provide insights into the underlying physics essential for interpreting experimental measurements related to MZMs and Kondo systems. They open pathways for advancing both theoretical predictions and experimental verifications.\\n\\nThis comprehensive analysis of MZMs within the Majorana-Kondo system sheds light on critical interactions and provides a basis for future research in topological quantum computation and related fields.\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 488, \"prompt_tokens\": 4435, \"total_tokens\": 4923, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 0, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 3328}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-4o-mini-2024-07-18\", \"system