        "gen_ai.prompt.7.tool_calls.0.arguments": "{\"s3_uri\": \"s3://agentic-wf/mcp/arxiv_consolidated/download_article-3f4b474fcb286355fc6637db9295740bb01ce3fc.txt\", \"query\": \"core contributions\"}",
        "gen_ai.prompt.7.content": "",
        "gen_ai.prompt.8.role": "tool",
        "gen_ai.prompt.8.content": "the MZMs are decoupled from the QD-NL subsystem, and\n(a2) the SCE screening cloud with an A \u2297B BC. (b-d) Nu-\nmerical results for different JM. JK is chosen as 0.2 to display\nthe local moment fixed point at Simp = 2ln2. (b) The impu-\nrity entropy Simp.\n(c) The spin and charge components of\nthe correlation function. Both of them are normalized to the\nzero-temperature result \u02dcIi = Ii/Ii(T = 0).\ntemperatures.\nIn practical calculations, the integral is\nrepalced by a summation over the bath sites of the Wil-\nson chain, which is obtained by a tranformation from\nthe original Hamiltonian. Within the framework of full\ndensity matrix (FDM), the correlation functions can be\ncalculated with a single \u201cforward\u201d NRG sweep after ob-\ntaining the reduced density matrix for each site (See\nappendices for details).\nWe point out that our finite-\ntemperature correlator method can be applied to a broad\nclass of composite or artificial impurity systems, provid-.\n\nMZM that couples the rest electrons in the NL. As a re-\nsult, the Kondo fixed point becomes unstable, and a new\nenergy scale denoted TSCE emerges as the signature of\nthe IR fixed point. An A \u2297N boundary condition is met\nas temperature is lowered below TSCE (about 10\u221213 for\nJM = 1e \u22127). The Simp = 1\n2ln2 plateau indicates an in-\nfrared (IR) strong coupling fixed point (SCFP) induced\nby the decoupled MZM \u03b3\u22122, and the schematic is in Fig.\n2(a2). The physics of the IR SCFP is proved to be same\nas the two-channel Kondo model in the sense of the low-\nenergy-effective Hamiltonian and non-Fermi liquid exci-\ntations. The effect of the A \u2297N BC is also revealed by\nthe LDoS where the pseudospin-up part divide into two\ncomponents \u03c1\u2191and A\u2191. Each of them contributes half to\nthe resonance peak [31, 36].\nResults for the integrated correlation functions are\nshown in Fig. 2(c). For TSCE \u226aTK, the contribution of\nIC in the screening cloud IL \u2261IS + IC is neglectable..\n\nthe resonance peak [31, 36].\nResults for the integrated correlation functions are\nshown in Fig. 2(c). For TSCE \u226aTK, the contribution of\nIC in the screening cloud IL \u2261IS + IC is neglectable.\nHowever, one can see that at the Kondo fixed point\n(Simp = ln2 of the dark solid line in Fig. 2(b)), the spin\nscreening cloud (the blue curves in Fig. 2(c)) has com-\npletely established, while the charge cloud only start to\nestablish after T \u2272TK. For a medium JK = 1e \u22124, the\nSimp = ln2 plateau just disappears, as shown by the dark\ndashed line in Fig. 2(b). For a lager JK \u22731e \u22124, the\nlocal moment fixed point flows directly to the SCE fixed\npoint skipping the spin Kondo SCFP, and the screen-\ning process of spin and charge DoF can happens almost\nmeanwhile, as illustrated by the dotted lines in Fig. 2(c).\nThe physical meaning of the character temperatures be-\ncomes explicit now. The definition of TK is analogous to\nthe conventional Kondo temperature when a spin screen-.\n\nior with three characteristic energy scales TK, TSCE, TM\nin order. The SCE screening process, however, preserves\nto low temperatures under TK instead of disappearing\nwith the vanishment of the Simp = ln2 plateau (together\nwith the topological degeneracy), as shown by the charge\ncomponent of the correlation functions IC in Fig. 3(c)\n(red solid line).\nThe local spectrum of the MZM-QD\nsubsystem is plotted in Fig. 1(c).\nIf we turn up the value of \u03f5m until the Simp = 1\n2ln2\nplateau disappears, the two energy scales TM and TSCE\nbecomes the same.\nThis can be seen clearly from the\nevolution of IC.\nThe evolution also implies that the\nSCE screening is even enhanced by the MZM-MZM cou-\npling. Independently, the fading of the 1\n2 plateau of the\nanomolous LDoS A\u2191in Fig. 3(d) indicates the violation\nof the A\u2297N boundary condition. Thus it should be clar-\nified that, the establishment of the SCE screening cloud\ndoes not dependent on the existence of the A \u2297N BC.",
        "gen_ai.prompt.8.tool_call_id": "call_EqIxa5brsvaupMrooNU5RtoJ",
        "gen_ai.prompt.9.role": "assistant",
        "gen_ai.prompt.9.content": "The paper titled \"Multi-scale competition in the Majorana-Kondo system\" introduces the concept of Majorana zero modes (MZMs) as promising candidates for fault-tolerant topological quantum computation due to their non-Abelian statistics and topological protection. The authors explore how MZMs interact with quantum dot (QD) systems, modifying the Kondo resonance peak through an anti-Fano resonance and revealing a crossover from conventional Kondo spin screening to spin-charge-entangled (SCE) screening as temperature varies. They identify critical contributions including the emergence of a new energy scale associated with the SCE and the stabilization of screening processes even when the conventional Kondo fixed point becomes unstable. This research aims to illuminate the complex interplay between Kondo physics and Majorana modes, providing valuable insights into both theoretical predictions and experimental validation in condensed matter physics.",
